And as a major tech school...that is the ranking of many of the service members here.   It costs the mil more money in BAH and many many other aspects to keep it open here, just 'for old times sake'.  When it is not the best situated or more effective location for training everyone, moving everything to a larger, less expensive, and more isolated (not a coastal easier soft target) would not be a bad thing.  Really they should have moved it when they closed Ord, it is only the major petitioning and lobbying by the city and state for fear of losing too much money (like I said this is a financial sink hole, so yeah they wouldn't want all that revenue to leave) that kept it here.  
To be able to live here, doesn't imply you can thrive here on the ever shrinking budget.  With extremely limited land space and historical buildings to watch out for, it is also very limited in its ability to expand or improve on it's own infrastructure and mission capability. That being said, I don't think they will ever really move it because too many big wigs and retirees like that it is in such a tourist hot-spot and so both reminiscing and self-placed importance of their memories and loss of access to nifty perks for them will stymie any moves to relocate.

Also on Gigling Road, at the intersection with General Jim Moore Blvd, is the General Stilwell Community Center. Within the Stilwell Center is ACS (Army Community Service) and some FMWR (Family and Morale, Welfare & Recreation) offices. Hope those acronyms and locations make your transition here a little smoother. Great question! Surely many people wonder the same thing. We're working on getting you a response quickly from our suicide prevention and awareness people here on post.

The response from our professionals: There are many Soldiers still serving honorably today who have sought professional help for suicidal thoughts and feelings. Open communication and honesty not only saved their lives but likely saved their military careers as well. Any Soldier in the U.S. Army who is having thoughts or feelings of suicide is encouraged to talk to their chain of command, a medical or behavioral-health professional, or even a trusted friend or family member. Suicidal feelings are nothing to be ashamed of, and one should not let fear of punishment or disapproval prevent them from seeking help. Talking these feelings over with someone who cares is one of the most important things a suicidal person can do. 
As for the question "Can a person enlist in the Army with if he/she has a history of suicidal thoughts or feelings," that would best be answered by an Army recruiter. 
Any further inquiries about the Presidio of Monterey’s suicide prevention and awareness programs can be addressed to Whitney Bliss, Army Substance Abuse Program, at 831-242-4131.
